Cool, I was able to use frama-c to mechnically verify overflow freeness for secp256k1_fe_mul_inner and secp256k1_fe_sqr_inner (10x26).

Given the precondition:

```
requires (a/b[0] < 1073741824);
requires (a/b[1] < 1073741824); 
requires (a/b[2] < 1073741824);
requires (a/b[3] < 1073741824); 
requires (a/b[4] < 1073741824);
requires (a/b[5] < 1073741824);  
requires (a/b[6] < 1073741824);  
requires (a/b[7] < 1073741824); 
requires (a/b[8] < 1073741824);  
requires (a/b[9] < 67108864);
```

Both have output ranges of:

  S_r[0..8] ∈ [0..67108863]
     [9] ∈ [0..4194304]

Which is more strongly normalized than the results from PR91.

I can't get back to this for a couple of days, but I've taken note of the performance reports and will revisit the several variations I have.

@sipa I'll catch you on &#35;bitcoin-dev at some point (ryjz).

@gmaxwell frama-c looks useful, thx for the lead. It seems to be indicating tighter bounds than my napkin math.
